1
00:00:48,920 --> 00:00:49,955
Go!

2
00:00:53,640 --> 00:00:54,629
Go!

3
00:00:58,600 --> 00:00:59,669
What's that?

4
00:01:00,440 --> 00:01:01,509
It's a man!

5
00:01:02,640 --> 00:01:04,471
- What? Is he dead?
- No, sir.

6
00:01:04,680 --> 00:01:06,272
He's writing!

7
00:01:06,520 --> 00:01:07,475
Repeat!

8
00:01:08,120 --> 00:01:09,030
He's writing,

9
00:01:09,200 --> 00:01:11,919
sir, he's writing in a notebook!

10
00:01:12,160 --> 00:01:15,072
That man was not mad.
He was working

11
00:01:15,240 --> 00:01:18,869
with shrapnel whistling round him
because he couldn't wait.

12
00:01:19,120 --> 00:01:21,680
The contents of that notebook
were too important

13
00:01:21,840 --> 00:01:23,398
to write it down later.

14
00:01:23,560 --> 00:01:26,199
He had to do it
when his mind dictated,

15
00:01:26,360 --> 00:01:28,828
he couldn't put it off
a single second.

16
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:33,231
What was so important that
he would risk his life for it?

17
00:01:33,760 --> 00:01:36,638
What was he writing that
stopped him from standing up

18
00:01:36,800 --> 00:01:38,552
and running, like any other man
would have done?

19
00:01:42,920 --> 00:01:46,071
The "Tractatus
Logico-philosophicus",

20
00:01:48,440 --> 00:01:51,989
the most influential philosophical
work of the twentieth century.

21
00:01:52,520 --> 00:01:55,432
That soldier was called
Ludwig Wittgenstein,

22
00:01:55,600 --> 00:01:58,160
the man who set the limits
on our thoughts.

23
00:01:59,080 --> 00:02:01,674
The enigma that
he tried to decipher

24
00:02:02,320 --> 00:02:03,548
was the following:

25
00:02:07,560 --> 00:02:09,994
Can we know the truth?

26
00:02:12,800 --> 00:02:14,552
All the great thinkers
throughout history

27
00:02:14,720 --> 00:02:16,392
have sought a single certainty,

28
00:02:16,560 --> 00:02:18,391
something which
no one can refute,

29
00:02:18,560 --> 00:02:20,949
like "two and two make four".

30
00:02:22,040 --> 00:02:23,871
In order to find that truth,

31
00:02:24,040 --> 00:02:25,871
Wittgenstein used, in fact,

32
00:02:26,040 --> 00:02:30,192
mathematical logic. What better
means of obtaining a certainty

33
00:02:30,360 --> 00:02:33,750
than an immutable language,
free from the passions of men?

34
00:02:35,200 --> 00:02:39,034
He advanced slowly,
using equation after equation,

35
00:02:39,200 --> 00:02:41,839
with impeccable method,
until he reached

36
00:02:42,040 --> 00:02:43,758
a terrifying conclusion.

37
00:02:45,560 --> 00:02:48,028
There is no such truth

38
00:02:48,280 --> 00:02:50,475
outside of mathematics.

39
00:02:50,920 --> 00:02:52,558
There is no way of finding

40
00:02:52,720 --> 00:02:54,995
a single absolute truth,

41
00:02:55,160 --> 00:02:56,957
an irrefutable argument

42
00:02:57,120 --> 00:03:00,317
which might help answer
the questions of mankind.

43
00:03:01,880 --> 00:03:04,792
Philosophy,
therefore, is dead.

44
00:03:06,520 --> 00:03:09,114
Because "Whereof we cannot speak,

45
00:03:11,040 --> 00:03:13,554
thereof we must be silent. "

46
00:04:34,280 --> 00:04:35,838
Don't touch that, please.

47
00:04:36,360 --> 00:04:37,793
This is an Enigma machine!

48
00:04:37,960 --> 00:04:41,316
Just a copy. The original's in
the Imperial War Museum in London.

49
00:04:42,040 --> 00:04:44,270
Sorry to sneak in like that...
The door was open.

50
00:04:44,440 --> 00:04:47,989
Of course it was open. You surely
didn't expect me to get up

51
00:04:48,160 --> 00:04:49,639
and let you in
on these legs, did you?

52
00:04:50,080 --> 00:04:51,035
I'm...

53
00:04:51,240 --> 00:04:56,792
Martin, our new overseas
student lodger, I presume.

54
00:04:57,960 --> 00:05:00,190
- This man in the photo with you...
- Yes.

55
00:05:00,360 --> 00:05:02,351
That's Turing, Alan Turing,

56
00:05:02,960 --> 00:05:05,235
the man who deciphered
the Enigma code.

57
00:05:05,400 --> 00:05:08,392
Thanks to him, we won the war.

58
00:05:08,560 --> 00:05:10,596
Poor man died
such a strange death...

59
00:05:11,480 --> 00:05:14,392
a poisoned apple, like Snow White.

60
00:05:15,440 --> 00:05:16,919
And the one on the left?

61
00:05:17,080 --> 00:05:18,991
My husband, Harry.

62
00:05:19,160 --> 00:05:22,197
Harry Eagleton. He developed the
concept of fractional dimensions...

63
00:05:22,360 --> 00:05:25,397
He deserved a bloody Nobel prize,
but he hated sucking up

64
00:05:25,560 --> 00:05:27,949
to politicians.
Politicians or anybody.

65
00:05:28,120 --> 00:05:29,394
He never had many friends.

66
00:05:30,400 --> 00:05:32,595
He had one at least.
Arthur Seldom.

67
00:05:32,760 --> 00:05:34,830
Poor boy. He spent day

68
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:37,673
after day in the house,
tidying Harry's papers.

69
00:05:37,840 --> 00:05:41,355
He'd go without lunch or dinner,
going over the equations.

70
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:45,675
Eagleton tutored his doctoral thesis
on the logical series. In 1960,

71
00:05:45,840 --> 00:05:48,718
- wasn't it?
- I see you've done your homework.

72
00:05:49,040 --> 00:05:51,349
I know everything there is
to know about Arthur Seldom.

73
00:05:51,520 --> 00:05:53,715
In fact, Mrs. Eagleton,
it's because of him that I'm here.

74
00:05:53,880 --> 00:05:55,393
In Oxford, I mean.

75
00:05:56,160 --> 00:05:58,993
I know what you mean.
Seldom is... unique.

76
00:05:59,920 --> 00:06:01,638
Every prize,
every acknowledgement

77
00:06:01,800 --> 00:06:05,998
he's received over the years
has been a real joy for me.

78
00:06:06,800 --> 00:06:08,916
Careful, mother, or
your secret will be discovered.

79
00:06:09,080 --> 00:06:10,115
What secret?

80
00:06:10,280 --> 00:06:11,872
After daddy died,
you tried to marry him.

81
00:06:12,040 --> 00:06:14,873
How dare you!
That's not true.

82
00:06:15,040 --> 00:06:16,314
He's always been
like a brother to me.

83
00:06:16,480 --> 00:06:18,357
Only because there was no chance
of him being anything else.

84
00:06:18,520 --> 00:06:19,555
Beth!

85
00:06:20,480 --> 00:06:22,391
There's no doubt
Professor Seldom is a genius,

86
00:06:22,560 --> 00:06:24,676
but there's one area
he's no different from other men.

87
00:06:25,640 --> 00:06:27,153
He likes young girls.

88
00:06:27,320 --> 00:06:30,915
Beth, darling, couldn't you stop
being so spiteful just for a second?

89
00:06:31,080 --> 00:06:32,195
Sorry, mother.

90
00:06:32,400 --> 00:06:35,073
Take no notice of us.
We're like two bitter old spinsters.

91
00:06:36,160 --> 00:06:39,311
Thank you, mother, for tarring me
with the same brush.

92
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:41,230
I'm sorry,

93
00:06:41,400 --> 00:06:42,515
you are...?

94
00:06:42,800 --> 00:06:45,314
I sent a fax a few weeks ago,
about renting a room.

95
00:06:45,480 --> 00:06:47,118
Ah, our overseas student.

96
00:06:47,280 --> 00:06:48,918
Why don't you
show him to his room?

97
00:06:51,720 --> 00:06:53,233
If I'd known,
I'd have rented a tux.

98
00:06:53,680 --> 00:06:54,874
You look stunning.

99
00:06:55,120 --> 00:06:57,315
My daughter has
a concert tonight. That's all.

100
00:06:57,960 --> 00:06:58,676
A concert?

101
00:06:58,840 --> 00:07:01,115
I play the cello
in the Sheldonian.

102
00:07:01,360 --> 00:07:03,396
- It's the local amateur orchestra.
- Yes.

103
00:07:03,640 --> 00:07:05,835
We're not quite
the London Symphony.

104
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:07,115
I... I love the cello.

105
00:07:07,280 --> 00:07:10,477
Me too. Maybe it's because
it's all I get to cuddle

106
00:07:10,640 --> 00:07:11,709
- these days.
- Beth.

107
00:07:11,880 --> 00:07:13,233
Please.
You'll scare the young man.

108
00:07:13,400 --> 00:07:14,355
Mother.

109
00:07:14,600 --> 00:07:16,591
My daughter's suitors
tend not to be

110
00:07:16,760 --> 00:07:18,079
around very long.

111
00:07:18,240 --> 00:07:19,389
Difficult character, you know.

112
00:07:19,960 --> 00:07:22,793
Having an old lady hovering in the
door way doesn't exactly help either.

113
00:07:22,960 --> 00:07:25,315
Are you calling me a busybody?

114
00:07:25,480 --> 00:07:27,789
No, mother. You just want
to protect me, don't you?

115
00:07:28,320 --> 00:07:29,435
Of course.

116
00:07:29,680 --> 00:07:30,829
My mother has this theory

117
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:33,116
that unless a man lived
through the Second World War

118
00:07:33,280 --> 00:07:34,713
he's not to be trusted.

119
00:07:34,880 --> 00:07:35,596
My daughter

120
00:07:35,840 --> 00:07:36,795
thinks I've gone a bit

121
00:07:36,960 --> 00:07:38,188
gaga, but she knows

122
00:07:38,360 --> 00:07:39,156
I'm right.

123
00:07:39,760 --> 00:07:41,751
The Nazis changed the wheels

124
00:07:41,920 --> 00:07:44,832
on that damned machine
every bloody day,

125
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:48,390
that altered the code, and we
had to decipher it all over again.

126
00:07:49,040 --> 00:07:51,031
There were no computers
in those days,

127
00:07:51,440 --> 00:07:53,829
calculations were done by hand.

128
00:07:54,920 --> 00:07:56,239
You must have been very young.

129
00:07:56,400 --> 00:07:57,549
Time for me to go.

130
00:07:58,440 --> 00:07:59,919
Fancy a game of Scrabble?

131
00:08:13,720 --> 00:08:15,915
Well, this is your study.

132
00:08:16,360 --> 00:08:18,157
I trust you'll be comfortable.

133
00:08:18,320 --> 00:08:19,355
It's perfect.

134
00:08:19,520 --> 00:08:21,988
You should also be thinking
of a supervisor

135
00:08:22,160 --> 00:08:23,149
for your thesis.

136
00:08:23,320 --> 00:08:26,232
I've had one in mind
for a long time; Arthur Seldom.

137
00:08:30,320 --> 00:08:31,355
Your parents?

138
00:08:31,520 --> 00:08:32,509
Yeah.

139
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:36,275
Very American.
Is it close to the beach?

140
00:08:36,440 --> 00:08:40,194
Not at all.
It's the desert, Arizona.

141
00:08:40,400 --> 00:08:41,913
It actually happens to be my home.

142
00:08:42,880 --> 00:08:45,075
Really? Lovely.

143
00:08:45,960 --> 00:08:47,029
Anyway...

144
00:08:47,240 --> 00:08:48,593
all the studies are shared.

145
00:08:49,120 --> 00:08:51,190
Your colleague is
also an overseas student.

146
00:08:51,360 --> 00:08:52,918
I'm sure we'll get on fine.

147
00:08:53,440 --> 00:08:54,350
By the way,

148
00:08:54,520 --> 00:08:58,479
I think you'll find Professor Seldom
only works as a researcher now.

149
00:08:59,040 --> 00:09:01,873
I know, but the college told me that
he could supervise my doctorate.

150
00:09:02,040 --> 00:09:03,439
Who told you that?

151
00:09:03,800 --> 00:09:05,518
I've got a fax...

152
00:09:05,760 --> 00:09:06,431
here.

153
00:09:09,120 --> 00:09:10,155
I see.

154
00:09:11,040 --> 00:09:13,918
I'm sorry to say Mrs. Keeman

155
00:09:14,200 --> 00:09:16,111
was being rather over-optimistic.
Also,

156
00:09:16,280 --> 00:09:17,429
she no longer works here.

157
00:09:17,600 --> 00:09:19,830
But there must be some way,
perhaps if I speak to him...

158
00:09:20,160 --> 00:09:21,354
You're free to talk
to whoever you want,

159
00:09:21,520 --> 00:09:25,308
of course, but I must
warn you Professor Seldom

160
00:09:25,480 --> 00:09:28,233
is not one for
this sort of spontaneity.

161
00:09:28,400 --> 00:09:29,958
If you take my advice,

162
00:09:30,120 --> 00:09:33,032
I suggest you approach your studies
in a more realistic way.

163
00:09:33,200 --> 00:09:36,078
I'm sure you'll find some excellent
tutors among our teaching staff

164
00:09:36,360 --> 00:09:39,318
who will more than understand
the nature of your work.

165
00:09:59,160 --> 00:10:01,151
- Don't take it out on the wall.
- Walls?

166
00:10:01,760 --> 00:10:04,035
Don't talk to me about walls. That's
all you get in this fucking city.

167
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:07,956
Sorry, just letting off
a little steam.

168
00:10:08,120 --> 00:10:10,873
Well, at least they come in
handy for doing your homework.

169
00:10:12,160 --> 00:10:14,993
These? I was just trying to save
myself 15 years of practice.

170
00:10:16,400 --> 00:10:18,038
See, I'm trying to calculate
where I need to run,

171
00:10:18,320 --> 00:10:19,469
depending on where
the ball bounces,

172
00:10:19,640 --> 00:10:21,232
and what height it makes contact

173
00:10:21,400 --> 00:10:22,037
with my racquet.

174
00:10:22,680 --> 00:10:24,671
Makes it easier. Here.

175
00:10:30,280 --> 00:10:31,793
See? It works.

176
00:10:32,880 --> 00:10:35,997
Yeah, and what would happen
if you played against a person?

177
00:10:38,040 --> 00:10:39,393
There would be more variables

178
00:10:39,600 --> 00:10:42,512
but it would still be possible
to work out the trajectory.

179
00:10:44,200 --> 00:10:45,235
Please.

180
00:11:21,080 --> 00:11:22,274
Give me time.

181
00:11:22,920 --> 00:11:24,990
I have to rethink my calculations.

182
00:11:26,800 --> 00:11:27,755
Okay.

183
00:11:40,040 --> 00:11:41,155
Thanks for the beating.

184
00:11:41,880 --> 00:11:43,233
Do you want to continue
letting off steam

185
00:11:43,400 --> 00:11:44,753
on your own
or do you prefer company?

186
00:11:46,640 --> 00:11:48,278
Wednesday, same time?

187
00:11:48,520 --> 00:11:52,069
Yes. Bring a proper squash racquet.
Makes life much easier.

188
00:11:53,160 --> 00:11:54,115
Okay.

189
00:12:04,520 --> 00:12:07,637
I see you're picking up
the local customs very quickly.

190
00:12:07,800 --> 00:12:09,074
I try my best.

191
00:12:09,240 --> 00:12:11,037
Maybe she can help you
with your doctoral thesis,

192
00:12:11,200 --> 00:12:13,395
since uncle Arthur
is out of the question.

193
00:12:13,640 --> 00:12:15,153
- Can nothing be done?
- No.

194
00:12:15,960 --> 00:12:18,474
And if you're suggesting my mother
have a word with him, forget it.

195
00:12:19,080 --> 00:12:20,354
I wasn't suggesting anything.

196
00:12:20,920 --> 00:12:23,878
Do you really expect me to believe
you chose this house by chance?

197
00:12:24,840 --> 00:12:26,751
No, not by chance, no.

198
00:12:27,160 --> 00:12:28,309
Nothing happens by chance.

199
00:12:28,480 --> 00:12:30,118
I wanted to meet
your mother, that's true,

200
00:12:30,320 --> 00:12:32,117
but I never planned to use her.

201
00:12:32,280 --> 00:12:33,918
There's no need to apologize.

202
00:12:34,680 --> 00:12:36,636
I like people who
go for what they want.

203
00:12:36,880 --> 00:12:38,199
I wish I was more like you.

204
00:12:38,720 --> 00:12:40,631
You're not missing much,
I assure you.

205
00:12:40,800 --> 00:12:42,028
Oh, really?

206
00:12:42,200 --> 00:12:44,509
You come here from another country,
all on your own,

207
00:12:44,680 --> 00:12:46,910
and no sooner do you get here
than you make friends with a girl.

208
00:12:47,440 --> 00:12:49,829
With two, I hope.
At least that's what I thought

209
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:52,355
- until a moment ago.
- It's not just that.

210
00:12:52,840 --> 00:12:53,909
You're happy,

211
00:12:55,040 --> 00:12:56,473
you only have to look at
your face to see that.

212
00:12:56,960 --> 00:12:58,075
I try to be.

213
00:12:58,240 --> 00:12:59,355
How do you do it?

214
00:13:00,520 --> 00:13:01,555
It's easy.

215
00:13:01,720 --> 00:13:02,914
It's a case of going
with the flow.

216
00:13:03,080 --> 00:13:04,593
And what if it goes badly?

217
00:13:08,640 --> 00:13:10,471
I'd rather make mistakes
than do nothing.

218
00:13:10,800 --> 00:13:13,189
I'd rather mess up
than miss out completely.

219
00:13:14,040 --> 00:13:15,189
It works for me.

220
00:13:15,920 --> 00:13:17,114
You should try it.

221
00:13:28,760 --> 00:13:29,875
Just a minute!

222
00:13:33,680 --> 00:13:35,238
I thought you might
find this interesting.

223
00:13:35,400 --> 00:13:37,118
Seldom is giving a lecture
on his latest book

224
00:13:37,280 --> 00:13:39,032
at Merton College on the 24th!

225
00:13:39,200 --> 00:13:40,679
There's your big chance!

226
00:13:42,760 --> 00:13:45,194
There is no way
of finding a single

227
00:13:45,360 --> 00:13:48,716
absolute truth, an irrefutable
argument that might help to answer

228
00:13:48,880 --> 00:13:50,757
the questions of mankind.

229
00:13:51,960 --> 00:13:54,758
Philosophy,
therefore, is dead.

230
00:13:56,360 --> 00:13:59,238
Because "Whereof we cannot speak,

231
00:14:01,120 --> 00:14:03,793
thereof we must be silent. "

232
00:14:18,480 --> 00:14:21,517
Oh, it seems that
someone does wish to speak.

233
00:14:22,920 --> 00:14:25,593
It appears you are not
in agreement with Wittgenstein.

234
00:14:26,240 --> 00:14:29,869
That means either you have found
a contradiction in the arguments

235
00:14:30,040 --> 00:14:33,715
of the Tractatus, or you have an
absolute truth to share with us all.

236
00:14:33,880 --> 00:14:36,030
I believe in the number Pi.

237
00:14:40,360 --> 00:14:42,794
I'm sorry,
I didn't understand you.

238
00:14:42,960 --> 00:14:44,473
What was it
you said you believed in?

239
00:14:44,640 --> 00:14:48,792
In the number Pi, in the Golden
Section, the Fibonacci Series.

240
00:14:48,960 --> 00:14:51,428
The essence of nature
is mathematical.

241
00:14:51,840 --> 00:14:53,671
There is a hidden meaning
beneath reality.

242
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:57,675
Things are organized following
a model, a scheme, a logical series.

243
00:14:58,640 --> 00:14:59,834
Even the tiny snowflake

244
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:02,833
includes a numerical basis
in its structure. Therefore,

245
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:06,356
if we manage to discover
the secret meaning of numbers,

246
00:15:06,520 --> 00:15:08,875
we will know
the secret meaning of reality.

247
00:15:16,680 --> 00:15:17,715
Impressive!

248
00:15:18,880 --> 00:15:20,313
Translating his words into

249
00:15:20,480 --> 00:15:21,595
the Queen's English,

250
00:15:23,640 --> 00:15:24,914
we find ourselves
faced with a fresh,

251
00:15:25,120 --> 00:15:28,157
rousing defence of mathematics,
as if numbers

252
00:15:28,320 --> 00:15:30,709
were pre-existing ideas in reality.

253
00:15:31,120 --> 00:15:33,315
Anyway, this is nothing new.

254
00:15:33,800 --> 00:15:36,633
Since man is incapable
of reconciling mind and matter,

255
00:15:36,800 --> 00:15:39,951
he tends to confer
some sort of entity on ideas,

256
00:15:40,120 --> 00:15:43,317
because he cannot bear the notion
that the purely abstract

257
00:15:43,480 --> 00:15:45,948
only exists in our brain.

258
00:15:49,280 --> 00:15:52,955
The beauty and harmony
of a snowflake.

259
00:15:56,480 --> 00:15:57,595
How sweet!

260
00:15:57,840 --> 00:15:58,875
The butterfly

261
00:15:59,040 --> 00:16:00,519
that flutters its wings

262
00:16:00,680 --> 00:16:03,558
and causes a hurricane
on the other side of the world.

263
00:16:03,960 --> 00:16:06,554
We've been hearing about
that damn butterfly for decades,

264
00:16:06,720 --> 00:16:10,679
but who has been able
to predict a single hurricane?

265
00:16:16,520 --> 00:16:17,839
Nobody!

266
00:16:22,760 --> 00:16:23,909
Tell me something...

267
00:16:24,720 --> 00:16:28,395
Where is the beauty
and harmony in cancer?

268
00:16:29,240 --> 00:16:31,037
What makes a cell

269
00:16:31,200 --> 00:16:33,589
suddenly decide to turn itself
into a killer metastasis

270
00:16:33,760 --> 00:16:37,116
and destroy the rest of
the cells in a healthy body?

271
00:16:38,840 --> 00:16:40,068
Does anyone know?

272
00:16:42,840 --> 00:16:43,875
No.

273
00:16:44,720 --> 00:16:46,995
Because we'd rather think
of snowflakes

274
00:16:47,160 --> 00:16:49,230
and butterflies than of pain,

275
00:16:49,960 --> 00:16:51,188
war

276
00:16:51,720 --> 00:16:53,392
or that book.

277
00:16:54,600 --> 00:16:55,794
Why?

278
00:16:56,400 --> 00:17:00,234
Because we need to think
that life has meaning,

279
00:17:00,760 --> 00:17:03,433
that everything
is governed by logic

280
00:17:03,600 --> 00:17:05,636
and not by mere chance.

281
00:17:06,600 --> 00:17:11,196
If I write 2 then 4 then 6,
then we feel good, because we know

282
00:17:11,360 --> 00:17:12,918
that next comes 8.

283
00:17:13,080 --> 00:17:14,479
We can foresee it,

284
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:16,877
we are not in the hands

285
00:17:17,040 --> 00:17:18,234
of destiny.

286
00:17:19,720 --> 00:17:21,631
Unfortunately, however,

287
00:17:22,960 --> 00:17:26,032
this has nothing to do with truth.

288
00:17:27,400 --> 00:17:28,799
Don't you agree?

289
00:17:31,560 --> 00:17:32,470
This...

290
00:17:34,120 --> 00:17:35,439
is only fear.

291
00:17:39,560 --> 00:17:40,754
Sad...

292
00:17:42,720 --> 00:17:43,948
but there you go.

293
00:17:54,720 --> 00:17:55,596
You must

294
00:17:55,840 --> 00:17:57,398
be Martin.

295
00:17:57,720 --> 00:17:59,358
At last we meet.

296
00:17:59,760 --> 00:18:02,115
But, I don't get it,
are you leaving?

297
00:18:02,280 --> 00:18:05,317
Yes, I'm leaving. It was a mistake.
It was all a big mistake.

298
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:09,389
Things have not turned out
as you expected, I guess.

299
00:18:09,560 --> 00:18:11,949
No, they haven't.
You bet they haven't.

300
00:18:12,600 --> 00:18:14,272
I hope the hastiness
of your decision

301
00:18:14,440 --> 00:18:15,429
has nothing to do with

302
00:18:15,600 --> 00:18:16,510
Professor Seldom.

303
00:18:17,880 --> 00:18:19,438
News travels fast in Oxford.

304
00:18:19,600 --> 00:18:22,398
We are a little village of gossips.

305
00:18:23,440 --> 00:18:26,352
Anyway, I think you are wrong
about the great sage.

306
00:18:27,120 --> 00:18:29,076
He was the best in his day, but...

307
00:18:29,240 --> 00:18:32,152
now he just wants to sell books.
Like those assholes.

308
00:18:32,320 --> 00:18:33,594
A real Seldom fan, eh?

309
00:18:34,880 --> 00:18:36,871
I have a framed photo
of him in my room.

310
00:18:37,040 --> 00:18:38,268
So he refused you too?

311
00:18:39,520 --> 00:18:42,796
I would rather jump out of
a window than ask him for help.

312
00:18:42,960 --> 00:18:45,997
I want nothing to do
with him or his books.

313
00:18:47,200 --> 00:18:48,997
I prefer the Reader's Digest.

314
00:19:19,400 --> 00:19:20,276
Taxi!

315
00:19:38,800 --> 00:19:39,437
Hello.

316
00:19:39,640 --> 00:19:42,438
Ah, we've got
the book you wanted!

317
00:19:45,520 --> 00:19:46,635
There.

318
00:21:26,520 --> 00:21:27,873
Fucking hell!

319
00:21:29,440 --> 00:21:30,634
What are you doing here?

320
00:21:31,160 --> 00:21:32,434
I live here.
What's your excuse?

321
00:21:33,800 --> 00:21:35,791
I came to visit an old friend.

322
00:21:36,680 --> 00:21:38,193
I'm sorry about before.

323
00:21:38,360 --> 00:21:40,032
No, don't apologize.
I talked a lot of rubbish.

324
00:21:40,200 --> 00:21:41,599
I tend to overact
when I have an audience.

325
00:21:41,840 --> 00:21:43,558
The truth is I just wanted
to attract your attention.

326
00:21:45,120 --> 00:21:46,394
You succeeded.

327
00:21:55,320 --> 00:21:56,639
September the 24th,

328
00:21:56,800 --> 00:21:59,360
1993. Inspector Petersen,
Oxford police station.

329
00:21:59,520 --> 00:22:02,751
Investigating the murder
of Mrs. Julia Eagleton.

330
00:22:03,440 --> 00:22:06,318
According to this report,
you and Professor Arthur Seldom

331
00:22:06,480 --> 00:22:09,233
discovered the body...
at the same time.

332
00:22:10,080 --> 00:22:12,310
Yes, we entered
the room together.

333
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:15,434
Are you one of
Professor Seldom's students?

334
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:16,955
No.

335
00:22:18,080 --> 00:22:20,116
- Do you work for him?
- No.

336
00:22:20,280 --> 00:22:22,510
Can you explain
why you were there together?

337
00:22:22,680 --> 00:22:23,669
No.

338
00:22:25,520 --> 00:22:27,158
To tell you the truth, I can't.

339
00:22:27,880 --> 00:22:29,359
I was also surprised
to see him there.

340
00:22:30,560 --> 00:22:32,835
So it was pure coincidence?

341
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:35,309
Everything seems to point
to that being the case.

342
00:22:37,520 --> 00:22:41,798
And was this the first time
you'd seen Professor Seldom?

343
00:22:41,960 --> 00:22:45,475
Not exactly. I was at
a conference he gave this morning.

344
00:22:46,560 --> 00:22:48,073
I asked him a few questions.

345
00:22:48,560 --> 00:22:49,709
What sort of questions?

346
00:22:50,200 --> 00:22:51,269
Mathematical ones.

347
00:23:00,360 --> 00:23:02,271
It's not by chance that I went

348
00:23:02,440 --> 00:23:03,793
to Mrs. Eagleton's house
this afternoon.

349
00:23:04,400 --> 00:23:06,630
I went there because
the murderer told me to.

350
00:23:06,800 --> 00:23:08,313
The murderer warned you?

351
00:23:08,960 --> 00:23:11,997
Yes, I received a note
during the conference.

352
00:23:12,160 --> 00:23:13,673
What did it say?

353
00:23:14,080 --> 00:23:15,308
Just one sentence:

354
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:17,433
"The first of the series,"

355
00:23:17,880 --> 00:23:20,474
written in capital letters.
Underneath,

356
00:23:20,920 --> 00:23:22,751
Mrs. Eagleton's address

357
00:23:23,280 --> 00:23:24,474
and the time.

358
00:23:24,800 --> 00:23:26,233
Can we see it?

359
00:23:27,160 --> 00:23:28,070
No.

360
00:23:28,720 --> 00:23:29,709
Why?

361
00:23:30,800 --> 00:23:31,949
I threw it away.

362
00:23:32,360 --> 00:23:34,476
You threw away
a vital piece of evidence?

363
00:23:37,680 --> 00:23:39,875
Yes, well, let me explain.

364
00:23:40,800 --> 00:23:42,552
After the conference,

365
00:23:42,720 --> 00:23:45,632
I signed a number of copies.
When I'd finished, I set off home.

366
00:23:46,600 --> 00:23:50,673
And that is when I realized
that the address on the note

367
00:23:50,840 --> 00:23:52,159
was familiar

368
00:23:52,800 --> 00:23:54,518
but honestly, I...

369
00:23:54,680 --> 00:23:58,798
it just never occurred to me that
anything like this could happen.

370
00:23:59,600 --> 00:24:01,750
Of course, when I got there,
it was too late.

371
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:16,274
We should call the police.

372
00:24:16,480 --> 00:24:17,515
You're right.

373
00:24:19,040 --> 00:24:20,109
Call them.

374
00:24:22,880 --> 00:24:24,199
999.

375
00:24:24,360 --> 00:24:25,315
Hello,

376
00:24:25,480 --> 00:24:27,471
I'm calling to report a death.

377
00:24:28,520 --> 00:24:30,078
3 Cunliffe Close.

378
00:24:31,960 --> 00:24:33,109
It's an old woman.

379
00:24:34,320 --> 00:24:35,275
Thank you.

380
00:24:36,880 --> 00:24:38,154
What do you think happened?

381
00:24:38,600 --> 00:24:39,715
I don't know.

382
00:24:40,360 --> 00:24:42,669
We should wait outside.
We'd better not touch anything.

383
00:24:42,840 --> 00:24:44,353
I shouldn't have
even used this phone.

384
00:24:44,600 --> 00:24:47,717
Try to etch on your memory
everything you can see.

385
00:24:47,880 --> 00:24:49,916
This moment is crucial.

386
00:24:50,240 --> 00:24:52,231
She was playing Scrabble
when it happened.

387
00:24:52,480 --> 00:24:53,595
Was she playing on her own?

388
00:24:54,080 --> 00:24:56,753
Yes, she has both
the letter racks on her side.

389
00:24:57,240 --> 00:24:58,753
You don't think she's been killed?

390
00:25:00,320 --> 00:25:02,038
I can't see any other alternative.

391
00:25:05,840 --> 00:25:08,070
Whoever did this obviously
intended to smother her

392
00:25:08,280 --> 00:25:09,429
with the cushion
while she was sleeping.

393
00:25:09,600 --> 00:25:11,238
She wakes up, puts up a struggle,

394
00:25:11,480 --> 00:25:13,948
he presses down harder,
using both hands perhaps,

395
00:25:14,120 --> 00:25:16,475
breaks her nose, hence the blood.

396
00:25:16,880 --> 00:25:18,359
Or it could have been a woman,

397
00:25:18,520 --> 00:25:20,875
using her knee
to add extra pressure.

398
00:25:21,840 --> 00:25:24,195
When the killer removes
the cushion, sees the blood,

399
00:25:24,360 --> 00:25:25,873
he drops it on the carpet
and doesn't even bother

400
00:25:26,040 --> 00:25:27,598
to put anything back in its place.

401
00:25:27,760 --> 00:25:29,113
Scared, probably.

402
00:25:31,560 --> 00:25:32,470
In the book

403
00:25:32,640 --> 00:25:35,712
that I based my conference on,
I unfortunately

404
00:25:36,080 --> 00:25:39,516
compare logical series
with serial murders.

405
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:42,150
And since its publication
I've received

406
00:25:42,320 --> 00:25:43,833
dozens of totally absurd letters,

407
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:45,592
which is why I attached
little importance to this one.

408
00:25:45,960 --> 00:25:47,951
And you're sure you destroyed it?

409
00:25:48,760 --> 00:25:51,718
Well, no, I threw it away
in the street.

410
00:25:51,880 --> 00:25:52,869
Where?

411
00:25:55,760 --> 00:25:57,478
Well, somewhere near
the Sheldonian Theatre.

412
00:25:57,640 --> 00:26:00,393
Scott, get on to it,
it might still be there.

413
00:26:00,560 --> 00:26:02,118
The road sweepers
will have passed through by now.

414
00:26:02,280 --> 00:26:05,352
It doesn't matter. We'll search
the dustcarts, if necessary.

415
00:26:05,960 --> 00:26:09,669
Now is there anything else? Anything
else that caught your attention?

416
00:26:09,840 --> 00:26:12,354
Oh, uh, under the text

417
00:26:13,200 --> 00:26:15,111
there was a hand-drawn circle,

418
00:26:16,360 --> 00:26:17,873
a perfect circle,

419
00:26:19,320 --> 00:26:20,912
also in black.

420
00:26:22,440 --> 00:26:23,668
About...

421
00:26:26,280 --> 00:26:28,032
this size,

422
00:26:29,920 --> 00:26:31,035
approximately.

423
00:26:32,960 --> 00:26:34,075
A circle?

424
00:26:34,920 --> 00:26:36,035
Like a signature?

425
00:26:36,240 --> 00:26:38,310
Oh no, I'm almost convinced
it was a symbol,

426
00:26:38,480 --> 00:26:40,357
the first element
of a logical series.

427
00:26:41,600 --> 00:26:43,397
Well, excuse my ignorance,

428
00:26:43,600 --> 00:26:46,273
I must have been off school
the day they taught

429
00:26:46,440 --> 00:26:47,589
logical series.

430
00:26:48,320 --> 00:26:49,514
A logical series

431
00:26:49,680 --> 00:26:51,238
is a group of elements
that succeed one another,

432
00:26:51,440 --> 00:26:52,668
following a particular rule.

433
00:26:52,840 --> 00:26:53,909
Could be 1, 2, 3, 4...

434
00:26:54,080 --> 00:26:56,389
or even numbers, 2, 4, 6, 8...

435
00:26:57,200 --> 00:26:59,634
Or of course it could be
the Fibonacci series.

436
00:27:00,160 --> 00:27:01,479
Fibonacci?

437
00:27:01,640 --> 00:27:03,039
A 12th-century mathematician.

438
00:27:03,200 --> 00:27:07,512
Each element is the sum of the two
previous ones: 1, 1, 2, 3, 5,

439
00:27:07,680 --> 00:27:10,240
- 8, 13...
- Look, I still don't see

440
00:27:10,400 --> 00:27:13,233
the relationship between
the murder and these series.

441
00:27:13,400 --> 00:27:16,710
I'm sorry. In my book I sustain
the theory that the murder committed

442
00:27:16,920 --> 00:27:19,912
for intellectual reasons
does not exist in the real world.

443
00:27:20,920 --> 00:27:23,832
In general, the patterns
followed by a serial killer

444
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:27,390
are crude, monotonous
and repetitive,

445
00:27:27,560 --> 00:27:30,711
cases that can be analyzed
psychologically, not logically.

446
00:27:30,880 --> 00:27:34,395
So you think the murderer is
killing to prove something to you?

447
00:27:35,280 --> 00:27:38,113
Yes, sadly, I believe
that to be the case.

448
00:27:38,560 --> 00:27:40,039
Murderer wants to prove me wrong.

449
00:27:40,200 --> 00:27:41,918
He wants to show that
he's more intelligent than I am

450
00:27:42,080 --> 00:27:43,433
and that he can beat me

451
00:27:43,600 --> 00:27:46,592
at my own game.
Somehow he knew of my friendship

452
00:27:46,760 --> 00:27:50,116
with Mrs. Eagleton,
and decided to begin there.

453
00:27:50,280 --> 00:27:52,714
How about this circle?
How do you explain this?

454
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:55,434
Oh, a circle's a good way
to start a logical series.

455
00:27:55,600 --> 00:27:57,113
There's no symbol
more indeterminate.

456
00:27:57,320 --> 00:27:58,799
Could mean almost anything.

457
00:27:58,960 --> 00:28:02,748
So you mean there's gonna be
another murder after this one?

458
00:28:03,080 --> 00:28:04,274
I'm afraid so.

459
00:28:06,280 --> 00:28:07,998
And if we don't
discover it in time,

460
00:28:08,320 --> 00:28:09,958
could be many more.

461
00:28:10,120 --> 00:28:11,712
Okay, we are going to change

462
00:28:11,880 --> 00:28:14,235
some notes please in part 12.

463
00:28:14,440 --> 00:28:16,908
We knew she was going
to die at any time,

464
00:28:17,840 --> 00:28:19,273
but never like this.

465
00:28:19,640 --> 00:28:22,518
The doctors gave her 6 months
to live, 5 years ago.

466
00:28:22,880 --> 00:28:25,952
Thanks to Beth's nursing
she had an extra lease of life,

467
00:28:26,440 --> 00:28:27,839
like a blessing from heaven.

468
00:28:28,880 --> 00:28:30,757
Maybe that's why
the murderer chose her.

469
00:28:31,880 --> 00:28:33,074
How do you mean?

470
00:28:33,360 --> 00:28:35,749
If he is trying to demonstrate
something purely intellectual,

471
00:28:35,920 --> 00:28:38,229
maybe the deaths in themselves
don't interest him.

472
00:28:38,440 --> 00:28:41,238
Maybe his aim is to inflict
as little harm as possible.

473
00:28:41,400 --> 00:28:43,436
He chose someone
that should have died.

474
00:28:43,600 --> 00:28:45,830
He probably knew Mrs. Eagleton
was receiving treatment...

475
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:48,195
She went every week
to St Joseph's hospital.

476
00:28:48,360 --> 00:28:51,670
He could have found out about her
illness there, and that made her

477
00:28:51,840 --> 00:28:53,558
the perfect victim for him.

478
00:28:53,880 --> 00:28:54,915
Go on.

479
00:28:56,080 --> 00:28:57,752
If he hadn't broken her nose,

480
00:28:57,920 --> 00:28:59,990
it would have looked
like death by natural causes.

481
00:29:00,280 --> 00:29:02,236
In that case, only you
would have known what happened.

482
00:29:02,400 --> 00:29:03,992
The police would never
have been involved.

483
00:29:04,240 --> 00:29:06,196
It would have been
a private challenge.

484
00:29:06,400 --> 00:29:08,152
A murder that almost isn't a murder.

485
00:29:08,320 --> 00:29:09,912
That makes sense.

486
00:29:11,120 --> 00:29:12,633
What do you think
he would do next?

487
00:29:13,320 --> 00:29:15,436
I suppose he'll try
to be more careful.

488
00:29:15,920 --> 00:29:18,673
He'll commit another murder
that almost isn't a murder.

489
00:29:19,960 --> 00:29:22,554
An imperceptible murder...

490
00:29:27,360 --> 00:29:28,509
Excuse me.

491
00:29:33,320 --> 00:29:35,788
Excuse me, officers,
but I need to speak

492
00:29:35,960 --> 00:29:37,598
to Miss Eagleton first,
to break the bad news,

493
00:29:37,760 --> 00:29:39,910
to her, if that's all right.
Thank you.

494
00:29:46,400 --> 00:29:47,719
You have a C,

495
00:29:47,880 --> 00:29:50,599
B flat, and C sharp.

496
00:29:50,760 --> 00:29:52,478
Excuse me, please,
I can talk to him?

497
00:29:52,640 --> 00:29:55,313
Yes, so

498
00:29:55,480 --> 00:29:56,799
you have a C, B flat,

499
00:29:56,960 --> 00:29:58,279
and C sharp.

500
00:29:59,840 --> 00:30:02,673
Oh, no, no, no. You have a B,
a C sharp, and C natural...

501
00:30:03,760 --> 00:30:04,749
Oh, okay,

502
00:30:05,320 --> 00:30:06,878
let's do a break, please.

503
00:30:40,400 --> 00:30:42,595
The police told me that you
were the one who found the body.

504
00:30:42,760 --> 00:30:44,352
Forgive me, Beth.
I'm really sorry.

505
00:30:44,520 --> 00:30:46,476
They asked me to try
and remember every detail and...

506
00:30:46,640 --> 00:30:49,473
It's no problem.
I understand.

507
00:30:52,600 --> 00:30:54,477
It must have been difficult
for you to go through all of this.

508
00:30:55,560 --> 00:30:57,471
Two hours of interrogation.

509
00:30:57,800 --> 00:31:00,473
It's logical, though, bearing
in mind I'm the chief suspect.

510
00:31:00,640 --> 00:31:01,789
Did they tell you that?

511
00:31:01,960 --> 00:31:04,520
No. No, they didn't have to.

512
00:31:05,800 --> 00:31:07,074
You don't need to be
a detective to realize

513
00:31:07,240 --> 00:31:08,992
that I'm the one who
most benefits from all this.

514
00:31:09,160 --> 00:31:12,391
But you looked after her
for years. Seldom told me.

515
00:31:13,520 --> 00:31:14,589
Five years...

516
00:31:15,320 --> 00:31:17,709
Five years of waiting
for her to drop dead.

517
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:20,672
Forgive me for being
so cruelly sincere,

518
00:31:20,840 --> 00:31:22,910
but if anyone wanted this
to end, it was me.

519
00:31:26,480 --> 00:31:28,835
Do you know what it is
to wake up every morning

520
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:31,468
wondering when you're going
to have a life of your own?

521
00:31:32,120 --> 00:31:34,429
I couldn't abandon her,
she was my mother.

522
00:31:35,280 --> 00:31:38,477
She had cancer but it was supposed
to be a question of months.

523
00:31:41,160 --> 00:31:43,799
You want this person you're supposed
to be looking after to disappear

524
00:31:43,960 --> 00:31:45,075
and at the same time you know

525
00:31:45,240 --> 00:31:46,639
there's something evil in you
for thinking that way.

526
00:31:48,680 --> 00:31:49,749
You hate yourself

527
00:31:49,920 --> 00:31:51,512
for the thoughts
that go through your head.

528
00:31:52,400 --> 00:31:53,879
It's like being rotten inside.

529
00:31:54,040 --> 00:31:56,508
Beth, you've no need to worry.

530
00:31:57,320 --> 00:31:58,594
Seldom got a note.

531
00:31:58,760 --> 00:32:01,069
Someone warned him of
what was going to happen,

532
00:32:01,240 --> 00:32:03,595
- and is threatening to do it again.
- Who?

533
00:32:03,760 --> 00:32:04,988
No one knows.

534
00:32:12,680 --> 00:32:14,716
They made me go to the morgue
to look at the body.

535
00:32:16,040 --> 00:32:17,678
Her eyes were still open.

536
00:32:17,840 --> 00:32:19,114
Don't think about it.

537
00:32:24,840 --> 00:32:27,115
I don't think I can sleep
upstairs tonight.

538
00:32:27,400 --> 00:32:29,038
Is it okay
if I stay here with you?

539
00:32:40,840 --> 00:32:42,068
I'm sorry.

540
00:32:42,240 --> 00:32:43,958
Don't be... it's okay.

541
00:32:44,800 --> 00:32:47,837
I don't know what you must
think of me. I'm so embarrassed.

542
00:32:48,080 --> 00:32:49,832
Beth, please. Don't go.

543
00:33:05,160 --> 00:33:08,391
Congratulations! Your name
in the papers and with Seldom!

544
00:33:08,560 --> 00:33:11,358
Knock off the old lady
to attract attention, did you?

545
00:33:11,520 --> 00:33:13,078
Not so fast!

546
00:33:14,200 --> 00:33:15,633
Your friend is lucky.

547
00:33:16,200 --> 00:33:19,033
Always close to death,
but never touched by it.

548
00:33:20,880 --> 00:33:22,029
Didn't you know?

549
00:33:22,520 --> 00:33:23,714
Thirty years ago,
the four of them

550
00:33:23,880 --> 00:33:26,394
- were travelling together.
- What are you talking about?

551
00:33:26,560 --> 00:33:29,950
Mrs. Eagleton's husband
and Seldom's wife were killed.

552
00:33:30,320 --> 00:33:31,878
And guess who was driving.

553
00:33:33,160 --> 00:33:35,549
And now the old lady is dead.

554
00:33:36,120 --> 00:33:38,031
Three down, one to go.

555
00:33:41,240 --> 00:33:42,958
This is Miss Scarlet

556
00:33:43,120 --> 00:33:45,429
and she is in the dining room.
Now we know that the murder

557
00:33:45,600 --> 00:33:46,476
took place in the dining room,

558
00:33:46,640 --> 00:33:48,551
don't we? And that the victim
was killed with a cushion,

559
00:33:48,720 --> 00:33:49,789
but since we don't have

560
00:33:49,960 --> 00:33:52,110
a cushion, we'll use
the nasty little knife.

561
00:33:53,920 --> 00:33:54,750
Now I'll stick

562
00:33:54,920 --> 00:33:56,876
my neck out and say that
Miss Scarlet was the murderer

563
00:33:57,040 --> 00:33:58,951
in the living room,
with the knife.

564
00:34:00,120 --> 00:34:01,189
What do you think?

565
00:34:01,360 --> 00:34:03,476
Clue didn't figure
into my degree course.

566
00:34:03,640 --> 00:34:04,709
Cleudo!

567
00:34:05,960 --> 00:34:07,393
It's recommended reading
in police academies.

568
00:34:08,800 --> 00:34:09,994
In the papers,

569
00:34:10,840 --> 00:34:13,354
Beth appears as the chief suspect.

570
00:34:13,520 --> 00:34:14,873
But the police know all the facts.

571
00:34:16,960 --> 00:34:20,794
Ah, I forgot that I was talking
to the champion of universal logic.

572
00:34:21,200 --> 00:34:22,155
Thank you.

573
00:34:22,760 --> 00:34:26,036
You and the police think that it's
possible to demonstrate the truth.

574
00:34:26,400 --> 00:34:27,071
On the basis

575
00:34:27,240 --> 00:34:29,196
of certain axioms
and by using valid reasoning,

576
00:34:29,400 --> 00:34:31,834
you can reach a valid conclusion,
isn't that so?

577
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:34,150
As sure as today is Wednesday.

578
00:34:34,320 --> 00:34:37,596
And what if I say,
"All Britons are liars"?

579
00:34:38,600 --> 00:34:40,875
True, false
or impossible to prove?

580
00:34:41,400 --> 00:34:43,868
All right. There are
mathematical formulations

581
00:34:44,040 --> 00:34:46,679
that can neither be proved
nor refuted starting from axioms.

582
00:34:46,840 --> 00:34:48,512
Indeterminable propositions.

583
00:34:48,680 --> 00:34:51,319
Exactly, Gödel's
incompleteness theorem.

584
00:34:51,560 --> 00:34:53,835
So, even in your world
of mathematical purity,

585
00:34:54,000 --> 00:34:56,150
there are things
that can never be proven.

586
00:34:56,320 --> 00:34:58,356
Yes, but that is not the case here.

587
00:34:59,240 --> 00:35:00,514
There is a gap,

588
00:35:01,560 --> 00:35:05,155
there is a gulf between
what is true and what is provable.

589
00:35:05,360 --> 00:35:06,634
We can never be sure

590
00:35:06,800 --> 00:35:08,518
of all the facts about a phenomenon,

591
00:35:08,680 --> 00:35:11,638
and to lack just one, could change
everything. Even if we know

592
00:35:11,800 --> 00:35:12,710
that the murder

593
00:35:12,880 --> 00:35:14,632
took place in the dining room
with the knife,

594
00:35:14,840 --> 00:35:17,798
and that Miss Scarlet was there
at the exact moment of the murder,

595
00:35:17,960 --> 00:35:20,030
and that her fingerprints

596
00:35:20,200 --> 00:35:21,474
were on the knife,
we can never

597
00:35:21,640 --> 00:35:24,518
affirm with absolute certainty
that she committed the crime.

598
00:35:24,680 --> 00:35:28,150
Oh, come on! It's
99% probable, for fuck's sake!

599
00:35:29,240 --> 00:35:32,277
That's not absolute certainty,
that is an opinion.

600
00:35:32,440 --> 00:35:34,078
We could have absolute certainty

601
00:35:34,240 --> 00:35:35,355
if we trusted the word
of an eye-witness,

602
00:35:35,520 --> 00:35:38,717
or we saw it with our own eyes.
I trust my own eyes.

603
00:35:40,320 --> 00:35:41,514
No comment.

604
00:35:41,720 --> 00:35:44,280
Things are here, under our noses.

605
00:35:44,440 --> 00:35:46,795
These paving stones. They exist!

606
00:35:46,960 --> 00:35:48,552
Or do you refute that
as well? You can't.

607
00:35:48,720 --> 00:35:51,280
Are you sure? Heisenberg
wasn't quite as certain.

608
00:35:52,120 --> 00:35:53,348
The physicist?

609
00:35:53,520 --> 00:35:55,715
Yes, well, he tried to make
an atom bomb for the Nazis,

610
00:35:55,880 --> 00:35:57,029
but he wasn't famous for that.

611
00:35:57,200 --> 00:36:00,317
What is this? An exam? Heisenberg's
"uncertainty principle".

612
00:36:00,480 --> 00:36:03,790
Bingo! Miss Scarlet
is now an electron, okay?

613
00:36:03,960 --> 00:36:05,598
And you're looking at her
through a keyhole,

614
00:36:05,760 --> 00:36:07,637
or a particle accelerator,
as you wish.

615
00:36:07,800 --> 00:36:09,028
And every time you look at her,

616
00:36:09,200 --> 00:36:12,670
Miss Scarlet will have
changed her appearance or...

617
00:36:13,240 --> 00:36:14,150
her position.

618
00:36:14,560 --> 00:36:16,152
Because the very fact
that you observe her

619
00:36:16,360 --> 00:36:18,715
alters her atomic state.
How about that?

620
00:36:18,960 --> 00:36:20,678
Don't try to confuse me with tricks.

621
00:36:20,840 --> 00:36:23,479
Beth is not an electron,
and neither is Mrs. Eagleton.

622
00:36:23,640 --> 00:36:25,835
So, do you really think
that criminal investigation

623
00:36:26,000 --> 00:36:28,150
is more reliable
than physics or mathematics?

624
00:36:28,320 --> 00:36:30,470
There are evident,
irrefutable facts.

625
00:36:30,840 --> 00:36:32,239
For Christ's sake,

626
00:36:32,400 --> 00:36:34,789
can you turn that bloody thing
off for a minute?

627
00:36:40,440 --> 00:36:43,238
Unfortunately, the police
were unable to find the note.

628
00:36:43,400 --> 00:36:46,278
Consequently, we have
no material evidence whatsoever.

629
00:36:46,440 --> 00:36:48,112
Not a thing!

630
00:36:48,680 --> 00:36:50,398
Imagine if that bloody psychopath

631
00:36:50,560 --> 00:36:52,915
gets the wind up
and decides not to kill again...

632
00:36:53,360 --> 00:36:55,874
Beth will be declared guilty.

633
00:36:59,360 --> 00:37:01,635
I'd love to know
who it is you hate so much.

634
00:37:03,920 --> 00:37:05,069
Myself.

635
00:37:06,200 --> 00:37:08,953
I read the news in the papers.
You're not to blame for anything.

636
00:37:09,480 --> 00:37:10,879
The worst thing is...

637
00:37:11,520 --> 00:37:12,999
This is embarrassing...

638
00:37:13,720 --> 00:37:16,109
Thanks to that
poor woman's death,

639
00:37:16,280 --> 00:37:17,679
I've just had lunch
with Arthur Seldom.

640
00:37:17,840 --> 00:37:21,150
Before, he didn't
even know I existed, but now...

641
00:37:21,440 --> 00:37:22,998
I'm sorry about what

642
00:37:23,200 --> 00:37:27,352
has happened but at the same time,
I swear I can't help feeling happy.

643
00:37:27,880 --> 00:37:30,075
Never, in my life, have I
enjoyed myself so much.

644
00:37:31,360 --> 00:37:34,909
One hour with Seldom is like
a lifetime with anybody else.

645
00:37:35,080 --> 00:37:36,957
Well, you know,

646
00:37:37,120 --> 00:37:38,838
there's nothing embarrassing
about sincere feelings.

647
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:41,228
Are you sure about that?

648
00:37:46,600 --> 00:37:48,192
Spend an hour with me?

649
00:38:16,760 --> 00:38:18,273
You have something to drink?

650
00:38:18,640 --> 00:38:19,914
- No.
- Great.

651
00:38:54,320 --> 00:38:56,151
- Are you okay?
- Yeah, are you okay?

652
00:39:08,200 --> 00:39:09,269
What's wrong?

653
00:39:09,440 --> 00:39:11,396
Nothing, it's... Sorry.

654
00:39:12,120 --> 00:39:13,109
It's Seldom.

655
00:39:13,280 --> 00:39:15,157
Just strange that you should
have read this book too.

656
00:39:15,320 --> 00:39:18,153
- A nurse interested in mathematics.
- Well, not really.

657
00:39:19,280 --> 00:39:21,919
It was the author who interested me.
He gave it to me.

658
00:39:22,560 --> 00:39:24,551
- You know Seldom?
- Of course I do.

659
00:39:24,720 --> 00:39:26,392
- See him almost every day.
- What?

660
00:39:28,720 --> 00:39:30,756
He visits a friend
at the hospital,

661
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:32,479
a terminal patient.

662
00:39:33,320 --> 00:39:35,311
One day we began to chat and...

663
00:39:35,480 --> 00:39:36,515
And what?

664
00:39:37,400 --> 00:39:38,992
And he gave me the book.

665
00:39:39,720 --> 00:39:42,075
- That's all?
- You're jealous?

666
00:39:42,240 --> 00:39:45,516
He could be your father... Your
grandfather, come to think of it.

667
00:39:45,680 --> 00:39:46,669
Yeah.

668
00:39:48,320 --> 00:39:50,436
I just like mystery novels,

669
00:39:50,800 --> 00:39:52,756
he was here for a while,
we had a laugh,

670
00:39:52,920 --> 00:39:55,195
I gave him a couple of my books
and he gave me his.

671
00:39:55,520 --> 00:39:58,239
- Is that a crime?
- No... Of course not.

672
00:40:01,880 --> 00:40:03,871
Can you get him out of your mind,

673
00:40:04,920 --> 00:40:05,557
please?

674
00:40:06,560 --> 00:40:08,710
I just don't understand why
you didn't tell me to begin with.

675
00:40:10,720 --> 00:40:11,835
What do you want?

676
00:40:12,400 --> 00:40:14,311
A list of all the people
who have passed through here?

677
00:40:15,120 --> 00:40:16,792
- No.
- Good.

678
00:41:20,000 --> 00:41:22,514
Everything you read
in the papers is a lie.

679
00:41:24,760 --> 00:41:25,749
Did you know that?

680
00:41:26,680 --> 00:41:28,079
No, uh...
I don't pay much attention.

681
00:41:28,240 --> 00:41:30,196
- Have you read the Bible?
- Not all of it.

682
00:41:30,680 --> 00:41:34,150
Jesus died on the cross
and then rose on the third day.

683
00:41:34,360 --> 00:41:35,634
But in body and soul,

684
00:41:36,360 --> 00:41:37,679
at least so they say.

685
00:41:38,280 --> 00:41:40,748
He ate fish and spoke to Peter.

686
00:41:40,920 --> 00:41:42,990
That's how he spent forty days.

687
00:41:43,360 --> 00:41:44,554
Forty days!

688
00:41:44,880 --> 00:41:47,758
He must have been green,
and have stunk to high heaven.

689
00:41:48,760 --> 00:41:50,159
Hey, wait, wait.

690
00:41:50,320 --> 00:41:51,639
Jesus was a terrorist.

691
00:41:54,480 --> 00:41:55,879
All his life.

692
00:41:57,000 --> 00:42:01,073
A revolutionary who kicked
money changers out of the temple.

693
00:42:02,360 --> 00:42:03,952
Do you know why
he came back from the dead?

694
00:42:04,120 --> 00:42:06,634
- No, theoretically...
- Jesus

695
00:42:06,960 --> 00:42:09,758
came back to life to avenge
himself on his murderers.

696
00:42:09,920 --> 00:42:10,909
Like in a horror movie.

697
00:42:13,160 --> 00:42:16,436
Of course, that's not nice.
That's not interesting.

698
00:42:18,040 --> 00:42:19,678
You can go in now,
your daughter

699
00:42:19,840 --> 00:42:20,875
- is expecting you.
- All right.

700
00:42:25,560 --> 00:42:26,913
What are you doing here?

701
00:42:27,080 --> 00:42:30,197
I had the urge to see you,
that's all. Do you mind?

702
00:42:30,760 --> 00:42:31,875
You're lying.

703
00:42:32,040 --> 00:42:33,109
How do you know?

704
00:42:33,400 --> 00:42:34,958
I didn't, I do now.

705
00:42:35,640 --> 00:42:37,756
You're here to see
Seldom's friend, aren't you?

706
00:42:37,920 --> 00:42:40,275
You should have seen the look
on your face when I mentioned him.

707
00:42:41,080 --> 00:42:42,957
And how are you going to explain
what you're doing here?

708
00:42:43,320 --> 00:42:44,992
I'll tell him I came to see you.

709
00:42:45,680 --> 00:42:46,829
You swine.

710
00:43:00,240 --> 00:43:02,037
Who is that guy?
He's nuts.

711
00:43:02,480 --> 00:43:04,789
Well, you would be too
if your daughter needed a transplant

712
00:43:04,960 --> 00:43:06,439
and you couldn't find a donor.

713
00:43:06,720 --> 00:43:08,233
There were two people
that could have been compatible,

714
00:43:08,400 --> 00:43:09,879
but their families refused.

715
00:43:10,200 --> 00:43:11,349
Now I get it.

716
00:43:11,680 --> 00:43:13,079
You know, he thought
of committing suicide

717
00:43:13,240 --> 00:43:15,151
in order to give her his lungs.

718
00:43:15,320 --> 00:43:16,833
That's ridiculous.

719
00:43:17,080 --> 00:43:19,310
Giving your life for someone
you love is ridiculous?

720
00:43:23,240 --> 00:43:24,275
His name is Kalman,

721
00:43:24,440 --> 00:43:26,158
one of my most brilliant students.

722
00:43:26,320 --> 00:43:27,469
He was quick in his conclusions,

723
00:43:27,640 --> 00:43:28,789
clear in his exposition.

724
00:43:29,320 --> 00:43:32,073
He designed intelligence tests.
I initiated him

725
00:43:32,280 --> 00:43:34,510
into the study of logical series.

726
00:43:34,680 --> 00:43:36,636
He was meticulous,
to the point of obsession.

727
00:43:36,800 --> 00:43:38,313
He marked the tests himself,

728
00:43:38,480 --> 00:43:39,754
one by one, and discovered

729
00:43:39,920 --> 00:43:41,194
something really curious:

730
00:43:41,360 --> 00:43:44,238
some of the tests were perfect;
the majority had a few mistakes.

731
00:43:44,400 --> 00:43:46,834
But there was a third group.

732
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:48,911
The answers were absurd,
incomprehensible,

733
00:43:49,120 --> 00:43:50,269
illogical, random,

734
00:43:50,440 --> 00:43:52,317
the sort of thing
that a lunatic would write.

735
00:43:52,480 --> 00:43:53,549
Kalman interviewed

736
00:43:53,720 --> 00:43:55,199
the pupils of this third category.

737
00:43:55,680 --> 00:43:57,557
The answers that
he had considered absurd

738
00:43:57,840 --> 00:44:00,115
were, in fact,
another possible solution

739
00:44:00,280 --> 00:44:01,110
and perfectly valid

740
00:44:01,280 --> 00:44:02,315
to continue the series,

741
00:44:02,480 --> 00:44:05,199
only with an infinitely
more complex justification.

742
00:44:05,680 --> 00:44:07,511
The intelligence
of these pupils

743
00:44:07,680 --> 00:44:10,274
went beyond
the conventional solution and was

744
00:44:10,440 --> 00:44:11,793
much more far-reaching.

745
00:44:14,520 --> 00:44:17,478
It was then that I had
to break the bad news to him.

746
00:44:18,560 --> 00:44:21,552
Wittgenstein's paradox
concerning finite rules.

747
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:23,752
Kalman found in practice

748
00:44:23,920 --> 00:44:25,672
what Wittgenstein
discovered decades before.

749
00:44:25,840 --> 00:44:26,989
The series 2, 4, 8,

750
00:44:27,160 --> 00:44:28,309
could obviously be followed

751
00:44:28,480 --> 00:44:30,869
by 16, but also by 10

752
00:44:31,200 --> 00:44:33,031
or 7004.

753
00:44:33,560 --> 00:44:35,994
It's always possible
to find a rule,

754
00:44:36,160 --> 00:44:37,752
a justification which allows

755
00:44:37,920 --> 00:44:40,036
a series to be continued
by any number.

756
00:44:40,640 --> 00:44:42,471
It all depends on
how complicated the rule is.

757
00:44:42,640 --> 00:44:45,473
Suddenly, he realized
that he couldn't even trust

758
00:44:45,640 --> 00:44:46,311
the two times table.

759
00:44:46,520 --> 00:44:49,114
His whole life was being
sucked into a whirlpool

760
00:44:49,280 --> 00:44:50,838
of meaningless numbers.

761
00:44:51,000 --> 00:44:53,719
Normal thought seems to be
guided by certain grooves

762
00:44:53,880 --> 00:44:55,711
etched into our brain

763
00:44:55,880 --> 00:44:57,393
which impede
our leaving that track

764
00:44:57,560 --> 00:44:59,198
and jumping it like the chosen few

765
00:44:59,360 --> 00:45:01,635
who are able to think
without limitations.

766
00:45:01,800 --> 00:45:04,155
Kalman decided
to take a strange path.

767
00:45:04,320 --> 00:45:05,912
He began to try out his tests

768
00:45:06,080 --> 00:45:08,799
in psychiatric hospitals,
on lobotomized patients.

769
00:45:08,960 --> 00:45:10,518
There was a remarkable similarity

770
00:45:10,680 --> 00:45:12,318
between those symbols

771
00:45:12,480 --> 00:45:13,833
and the results of the tests

772
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:15,194
of the highly-gifted subjects.

773
00:45:15,600 --> 00:45:17,750
He was in the presence
of pure thought,

774
00:45:17,920 --> 00:45:19,399
without grooves,

775
00:45:19,920 --> 00:45:22,036
but he couldn't understand it.
