01:25:01,489 --> 01:25:04,606
Seldom? What have you done?
You've got the wrong bus!

1524
01:25:29,329 --> 01:25:30,159
Hello?

1525
01:25:30,329 --> 01:25:33,241
Seldom, you have to speak with
Petersen, there's another bus!

1526
01:25:33,409 --> 01:25:34,444
What are you talking about?

1527
01:25:34,609 --> 01:25:35,883
It's the girl's father!

1528
01:25:36,049 --> 01:25:37,198
What girl?

1529
01:25:44,409 --> 01:25:45,478
Martin?

1530
01:25:46,289 --> 01:25:47,483
Martin, can you hear me?

1531
01:25:47,649 --> 01:25:50,402
The girl in the hospital,
she needs a transplant.

1532
01:25:50,569 --> 01:25:52,878
He wants to kill
the kids to save her!

1533
01:26:08,529 --> 01:26:09,484
Sir?

1534
01:26:09,649 --> 01:26:12,288
Excuse me, sir.
Sir, this way, please.

1535
01:26:12,929 --> 01:26:14,760
- That bus has to be stopped!
- Calm down, sir.

1536
01:26:14,929 --> 01:26:16,442
They're going to be killed!
I have to talk to Petersen!

1537
01:26:17,769 --> 01:26:20,488
Sir, one of the professors
insists on speaking to you.

1538
01:26:20,649 --> 01:26:22,048
He's completely
lost control of himself.

1539
01:26:39,009 --> 01:26:40,647
Oh what the hell...?

1540
01:26:55,009 --> 01:26:58,046
You.
Did you know about this?

1541
01:26:58,569 --> 01:27:01,037
Did you fucking know about this?

1542
01:27:01,209 --> 01:27:02,722
You and your fucking equations!

1543
01:27:13,969 --> 01:27:15,402
I don't know anything.

1544
01:27:21,129 --> 01:27:22,244
Nothing.

1545
01:28:10,049 --> 01:28:13,041
Five of the victims
are possible donors.

1546
01:28:14,249 --> 01:28:16,444
Five organs offer a fair chance.

1547
01:28:16,889 --> 01:28:18,117
They're rushing them off
to St Joseph's.

1548
01:28:18,529 --> 01:28:20,008
That's why he sent the ambulances.

1549
01:28:20,169 --> 01:28:21,602
That's right.

1550
01:28:22,769 --> 01:28:24,487
The petrol tank
was down to a minimum.

1551
01:28:24,689 --> 01:28:26,168
He wanted to cause
as little harm as possible,

1552
01:28:26,329 --> 01:28:29,127
only this time
it wasn't exactly imperceptible.

1553
01:28:30,169 --> 01:28:31,807
Why all these?
Why all the symbols?

1554
01:28:32,209 --> 01:28:34,279
He didn't plan
to die in the accident.

1555
01:28:34,449 --> 01:28:37,361
His idea was to jump in time
to avoid being a suspect.

1556
01:28:37,529 --> 01:28:38,245
How do you know?

1557
01:28:39,769 --> 01:28:42,522
When the bus crashed,
the doors were already open.

1558
01:28:43,809 --> 01:28:45,242
And what about the other deaths?

1559
01:28:45,889 --> 01:28:47,686
Well, if only the children
had been killed,

1560
01:28:47,849 --> 01:28:49,407
he would have been
the prime suspect.

1561
01:28:49,569 --> 01:28:51,287
Making us believe
in a serial killer

1562
01:28:51,449 --> 01:28:52,802
took the spotlight off him.

1563
01:28:52,969 --> 01:28:55,847
Only he miscalculated
and didn't get out in time.

1564
01:28:56,689 --> 01:28:59,157
So, he didn't really want
to kill the other people,

1565
01:28:59,529 --> 01:29:02,168
- he just needed an alibi?
- Exactly.

1566
01:29:03,009 --> 01:29:05,477
Shame we didn't work it out sooner.

1567
01:29:05,849 --> 01:29:06,838
So much

1568
01:29:07,009 --> 01:29:08,078
for logic.

1569
01:29:53,529 --> 01:29:55,804
You were just a pawn in his game.

1570
01:29:57,009 --> 01:29:59,125
You have nothing
to feel guilty about.

1571
01:30:08,209 --> 01:30:10,598
You don't know what you're saying.

1572
01:30:31,689 --> 01:30:33,566
You don't need to get on a plane.

1573
01:30:34,569 --> 01:30:35,604
Sorry?

1574
01:30:35,769 --> 01:30:39,045
I said, you don't need to get on
a plane. You're already miles away.

1575
01:30:39,649 --> 01:30:40,718
I was just thinking...

1576
01:30:40,889 --> 01:30:41,799
Really?

1577
01:30:46,169 --> 01:30:47,921
Ok.
From now on,

1578
01:30:48,089 --> 01:30:49,761
we are just two tourists

1579
01:30:49,929 --> 01:30:53,080
in an airport with the heaviest
rucksack I've ever seen.

1580
01:30:54,649 --> 01:30:56,002
What did you pack in here anyway?

1581
01:30:56,209 --> 01:30:58,882
Oh, you know, just the essentials.
A double bed, a cooker,

1582
01:30:59,049 --> 01:31:00,402
for making spaghetti

1583
01:31:00,569 --> 01:31:02,161
- and a couple of other things.
- Well, I hope

1584
01:31:02,329 --> 01:31:03,921
you didn't pack a single
one of your mystery novels.

1585
01:31:04,089 --> 01:31:04,760
Of course not!

1586
01:31:04,929 --> 01:31:07,682
No mystery novels,
no symbols, no Oxford.

1587
01:31:07,849 --> 01:31:09,487
We had a deal, remember?

1588
01:31:09,769 --> 01:31:11,202
You gonna be able to live like this?

1589
01:31:12,209 --> 01:31:13,278
Yes.

1590
01:31:13,449 --> 01:31:14,484
Just you and me.

1591
01:31:19,889 --> 01:31:20,799
Come on.

1592
01:31:29,289 --> 01:31:30,358
Thank you.

1593
01:31:39,049 --> 01:31:40,687
Can I have your
boarding pass, please?

1594
01:31:40,929 --> 01:31:42,078
He didn't know!

1595
01:31:42,409 --> 01:31:43,285
Martin?

1596
01:31:44,649 --> 01:31:45,638
That old fucker tricked me!

1597
01:31:47,249 --> 01:31:48,284
He didn't know
what the third symbol was!

1598
01:31:57,489 --> 01:31:58,558
My God!

1599
01:31:59,209 --> 01:32:00,801
You've got the pictures with you?

1600
01:32:02,169 --> 01:32:03,488
What is this?

1601
01:32:04,809 --> 01:32:05,685
"Kreis".

1602
01:32:09,049 --> 01:32:10,368
What is that?

1603
01:32:19,569 --> 01:32:22,447
She spent 3 years
deciphering German codes.

1604
01:32:22,609 --> 01:32:23,519
Excuse me, sir,
you can't do that here.

1605
01:32:23,689 --> 01:32:24,644
Of course!

1606
01:32:24,809 --> 01:32:26,959
Kreis is German for circle.

1607
01:32:27,369 --> 01:32:28,802
He came up with it on the spot!

1608
01:33:06,529 --> 01:33:07,848
Have you been here before?

1609
01:33:09,889 --> 01:33:11,322
I never had a chance.

1610
01:33:13,129 --> 01:33:16,360
It would be a pity to leave the
country without seeing this place.

1611
01:33:18,129 --> 01:33:19,244
This is the largest

1612
01:33:19,409 --> 01:33:21,559
collection of fakes in the world.

1613
01:33:21,809 --> 01:33:23,447
Not even Michelangelo

1614
01:33:23,609 --> 01:33:25,839
can distinguish
this David from his original.

1615
01:33:27,369 --> 01:33:30,520
Trajan's column
we believe to be in Rome,

1616
01:33:31,489 --> 01:33:35,801
but we are sure
that this is a common

1617
01:33:36,009 --> 01:33:37,965
plaster copy.

1618
01:33:39,049 --> 01:33:40,607
I feel at ease here.

1619
01:33:41,209 --> 01:33:43,245
No one tries to deceive me.

1620
01:33:43,849 --> 01:33:45,646
In effect, Martin,
this is the place

1621
01:33:45,809 --> 01:33:48,687
that contains the most truth
in the entire planet.

1622
01:33:49,849 --> 01:33:52,886
We have an absolute truth:

1623
01:33:54,009 --> 01:33:56,239
everything is fake.

1624
01:33:57,449 --> 01:33:59,201
Outside of these walls

1625
01:33:59,369 --> 01:34:01,325
nobody is sure of anything.

1626
01:34:04,169 --> 01:34:07,525
You took a big risk in giving me
a blank piece of paper.

1627
01:34:11,009 --> 01:34:14,206
That was important.
I had to convince you that I knew

1628
01:34:14,369 --> 01:34:17,167
what the sign was when, at
that moment, I wasn't at all sure.

1629
01:34:17,689 --> 01:34:19,645
I knew you wouldn't
let me down, Martin.

1630
01:34:19,809 --> 01:34:22,243
Your pride wouldn't let you open
this piece of paper

1631
01:34:22,409 --> 01:34:23,637
until you had
a solution of your own,

1632
01:34:23,809 --> 01:34:27,484
and that, if I might say,
was going to take some time.

1633
01:34:28,129 --> 01:34:29,847
There was no serial killer.

1634
01:34:30,529 --> 01:34:33,168
It was an invention,
just like Petersen said.

1635
01:34:33,649 --> 01:34:35,799
But it wasn't
the bus driver's invention.

1636
01:34:36,129 --> 01:34:37,118
It was yours.

1637
01:34:37,769 --> 01:34:40,886
You invented a series of killings
to hide the only real crime:

1638
01:34:41,449 --> 01:34:44,122
the death of Mrs. Eagleton.
Beth killed her,

1639
01:34:44,289 --> 01:34:46,564
just as the police had suspected
from the very beginning.

1640
01:34:51,689 --> 01:34:53,805
Beth hated her life.
She couldn't put up

1641
01:34:53,969 --> 01:34:55,766
with that woman any more
so she killed her.

1642
01:34:55,929 --> 01:34:57,840
That's when she sent you a note

1643
01:34:58,169 --> 01:34:59,488
asking for help.

1644
01:34:59,769 --> 01:35:01,646
I couldn't look her in the face.

1645
01:35:03,169 --> 01:35:05,319
It was my fault that her father
was killed in that accident

1646
01:35:05,489 --> 01:35:07,525
30 years ago.

1647
01:35:08,569 --> 01:35:10,127
I couldn't let her down again.

1648
01:35:10,289 --> 01:35:11,927
We both met at the door.

1649
01:35:12,249 --> 01:35:13,728
You'd come to get rid
of the evidence,

1650
01:35:13,889 --> 01:35:16,608
but I was there, in the way,
and that spoiled everything.

1651
01:35:17,889 --> 01:35:19,561
You had to come up with
a new plan, in front of me,

1652
01:35:19,729 --> 01:35:22,766
just moments before the police
arrived. You read the word

1653
01:35:22,929 --> 01:35:24,487
"circle" in German
on the Scrabble rack,

1654
01:35:24,649 --> 01:35:25,638
and that gave you the idea.

1655
01:35:27,169 --> 01:35:28,568
A series with
infinite possibilities.

1656
01:35:28,729 --> 01:35:30,367
But you needed a second death

1657
01:35:30,529 --> 01:35:32,804
to convince the police
that the murderer was not Beth.

1658
01:35:32,969 --> 01:35:34,766
And unwittingly, I helped you.

1659
01:35:36,649 --> 01:35:39,846
I gave you the idea of how
to do it, without even realising.

1660
01:35:40,169 --> 01:35:41,363
An imperceptible murder.

1661
01:35:41,729 --> 01:35:42,923
A murderer who only kills

1662
01:35:43,089 --> 01:35:43,999
someone who is at

1663
01:35:44,209 --> 01:35:45,358
death's door. You only had

1664
01:35:45,529 --> 01:35:47,884
to wait for the occasion
and prick the body with a syringe.

1665
01:35:48,329 --> 01:35:50,923
That's when you sent
the second message. The fish.

1666
01:35:51,689 --> 01:35:54,078
You still didn't know
where all this was going to lead.

1667
01:35:54,249 --> 01:35:57,161
The possibilities of continuing
the series were still infinite.

1668
01:35:57,329 --> 01:35:59,399
You had to wait for
another occasion to arise.

1669
01:35:59,569 --> 01:36:01,560
And that could take weeks, months.

1670
01:36:01,729 --> 01:36:02,923
There was no hurry.

1671
01:36:03,249 --> 01:36:05,763
You probably had a different plan
for the third death,

1672
01:36:05,969 --> 01:36:08,961
but that triangle player suddenly
appeared like a gift from the gods,

1673
01:36:09,889 --> 01:36:12,722
- and you had your solution.
- At first I rejected it.

1674
01:36:12,889 --> 01:36:14,083
Too many people, too operatic.

1675
01:36:15,289 --> 01:36:15,960
Don't lie.

1676
01:36:16,129 --> 01:36:17,039
You couldn't waste

1677
01:36:17,249 --> 01:36:18,398
a chance like that.

1678
01:36:18,809 --> 01:36:21,960
What's more, there was a triangle.
It all took on meaning!

1679
01:36:22,889 --> 01:36:25,562
Beautiful... It was as if
the damned Pythagoreans

1680
01:36:25,729 --> 01:36:27,162
were on your side.

1681
01:36:27,409 --> 01:36:30,048
It was perfect,
but what's more important,

1682
01:36:30,209 --> 01:36:31,927
it was totally inoffensive.

1683
01:36:32,249 --> 01:36:33,967
Until the madman appeared.

1684
01:36:34,729 --> 01:36:37,960
Any one of our acts can have
unexpected consequences.

1685
01:36:38,129 --> 01:36:39,244
That's what you most feared.

1686
01:36:40,489 --> 01:36:41,717
Who was to know that poor devil

1687
01:36:41,889 --> 01:36:43,880
was going to read
the article in the paper?

1688
01:36:44,049 --> 01:36:46,722
He was looking for a solution
to his daughter's problem,

1689
01:36:46,969 --> 01:36:49,688
while every day he drove to school
those healthy children

1690
01:36:49,849 --> 01:36:52,044
with perfect lungs
but damaged brains.

1691
01:36:52,569 --> 01:36:54,605
Why did they deserve to live
and not his daughter?

1692
01:36:55,089 --> 01:36:58,877
Mathematicians are not the only ones
familiar with the Greeks, professor.

1693
01:36:59,089 --> 01:37:02,161
You gave him his solution
when you published the series.

1694
01:37:02,329 --> 01:37:04,445
He also wanted to hide his crime.

1695
01:37:04,729 --> 01:37:06,924
He only had to make
a phone call, and he did.

1696
01:37:18,369 --> 01:37:19,518
So...

1697
01:37:21,209 --> 01:37:22,608
you think I'm the killer.

1698
01:37:23,529 --> 01:37:24,564
No.

1699
01:37:24,849 --> 01:37:26,487
You haven't killed anyone,

1700
01:37:27,009 --> 01:37:30,604
but you're guilty of provoking the
deaths of those innocent children.

1701
01:37:31,289 --> 01:37:33,086
You're guilty of arrogance,

1702
01:37:33,369 --> 01:37:36,042
of using us all like
pieces on a board game.

1703
01:37:37,089 --> 01:37:38,920
Who the hell do you think you are?

1704
01:37:41,809 --> 01:37:45,597
I hope my failure has, at least,
served to teach you something.

1705
01:37:47,489 --> 01:37:49,241
Yes, one thing.

1706
01:37:49,969 --> 01:37:51,960
One very painful thing.

1707
01:37:52,849 --> 01:37:54,646
Numbers also lie.

1708
01:37:55,089 --> 01:37:57,967
The truth is not mathematical,
as I once believed.

1709
01:37:58,369 --> 01:38:00,803
It's absurd, confused, random,

1710
01:38:00,969 --> 01:38:03,358
disorderly, and deeply unpleasant.

1711
01:38:04,169 --> 01:38:07,605
I'm glad that finally we can agree
on something, Martin, my friend.

1712
01:38:08,489 --> 01:38:10,639
Just one thing has escaped you.

1713
01:38:15,089 --> 01:38:16,647
The real culprit.

1714
01:38:18,249 --> 01:38:21,127
The one who triggered off
this whole string of crimes.

1715
01:38:21,289 --> 01:38:22,608
Who?

1716
01:38:22,769 --> 01:38:23,884
You, Martin.

1717
01:38:25,049 --> 01:38:26,198
Don't make me laugh.

1718
01:38:26,369 --> 01:38:28,644
If you don't believe me,
then speak to Beth.

1719
01:38:29,489 --> 01:38:31,047
She was in love with you,

1720
01:38:31,889 --> 01:38:33,447
or weren't you aware of that?

1721
01:38:34,769 --> 01:38:37,363
She remembered
your words exactly.

1722
01:38:38,969 --> 01:38:40,561
"You should try it. "

1723
01:38:41,129 --> 01:38:44,280
"You should try it,"
pounded time and again

1724
01:38:44,449 --> 01:38:46,326
inside her head, like a hammer.

1725
01:38:47,369 --> 01:38:49,564
"You should be free, like me. "

1726
01:38:51,889 --> 01:38:53,766
That's what she understood,

1727
01:38:55,129 --> 01:38:56,687
and that's what she did.

1728
01:38:58,049 --> 01:39:00,882
Put an end to what
prevented her from being free...

1729
01:39:04,209 --> 01:39:05,881
her own mother.

1730
01:39:07,209 --> 01:39:08,198
The butterfly

1731
01:39:09,609 --> 01:39:12,077
that flutters its wings
and causes a hurricane

1732
01:39:12,249 --> 01:39:14,126
on the other side of the world.

1733
01:39:16,529 --> 01:39:18,201
Sound familiar?

1734
01:39:21,009 --> 01:39:23,762
Are you that butterfly, Martin?

